\begin{center}
    \Large \bf {Abstract}\\
\end{center}

This report provides an extensive exploration of the Fundamental Theorem of Homomorphisms in group theory, a fundamental concept with profound implications across mathematics. Beginning with the foundational definitions and properties of groups, including illustrative examples to solidify understanding, we establish the groundwork necessary for deeper exploration. Subsequent sections delve into subgroups, emphasizing cyclic groups and their significance in the context of group theory. The concept of cosets is introduced, followed by an examination of normal subgroups and quotient groups, elucidating their roles in group structure and manipulation.
\\
\\

Central to this report is the comprehensive discussion on homomorphisms—functions that preserve the structure of groups—beginning with their definition and extending to their diverse applications. The Fundamental Theorem of Homomorphisms is the focal point, offering a profound insight into the relationship between homomorphisms, their kernels, and the quotient groups they induce. Through detailed proofs, examples, and practical applications, the theorem's theoretical underpinnings and practical utility are thoroughly explored.

